        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "but the rest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "said, Let be",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "said, Let be",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἄφες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This is a common expression, meaning, \"Stand off!\" \"Be quiet!\" \"Soft!\" The bystanders addressed the person who had presented the drink. In St. Mark the verb is in the plural, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἄφετε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, the giver of the drink calls upon the others to keep quiet and wait. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Let as see whether Elias will come",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἔρχεται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "cometh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is coming). They speak in a kind of superstitious mockery, half deriding and half believing in the possible appearance of the great prophet. Between this verse and the following, the Sinaitic, Vatican, and some other manuscripts, together with some few versions, insert a passage borrowed from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"And another taking a spear pierced his side, and there came out water and blood.\" This evident interpolation has been introduced by a scribe, who deemed it expedient to rectify an omission on St. Matthew's part, and clumsily inserted it in a wrong place. It is to be rejected, not only on critical, but on historical and theological grounds, seeing that it makes the piercing of the side to precede Christ's death, and conveys the impression that it was this spear wound that cut short his life. Matthew 27:49",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
